text: The old man and the sea is the story of a fight between and elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son of a bitch on planet earth. Honesty, if you were in a boat for eighty four days, it‚Äôd be hard NOT to catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as the Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄúParents just don‚Äôt understand‚Äù. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway, ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an eldery man who talks to himself. Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food, and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio, who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady Luck is returning. On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy lunch, Santiago drops his lines and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big-ass fish. He‚Äôs sure he‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in.Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚ÄúBrother‚Äù or maybe even ‚ÄúBro‚Äù. It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding. But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a fucking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words instead of giving in to base desires and imposing his gigantically terrible position on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, read to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding Marlin‚Äôs carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to fucking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky, REALLY unlucky (DUH!) Ma calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair, I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin. It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚ÄúDream killer‚Äù now, fuckface! The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said ‚Äì He‚Äôs super tired. The next morning, a group of fisherman gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (Strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later there‚Äôs a Red Lobster restaurant in nearly every city in America offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.  You're welcome

text: That piece of text at the end of the trailer:  The old man and the sea is the story of a fight between and elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like... HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty four days without catching a fish because he's the unluckiest son of a bitch on planet earth. Honesty, if you were in a boat for eighty four days, it'd be hard NOT to catch a fish... even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as the Fresh Prince used to say, "Parents just don't understand". So the boy visits Santiago's shack anyway, ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself. Manolin helps out, moving Santiago's fishing gear, making food, and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio, who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he's going way out into the gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady Luck is returning. On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy lunch, Santiago drops his lines and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big-ass fish. He's sure he's a winner. He fights and fights and fights and fights but can't pull the monster in.Santiago's leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he's bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him "Brother" or maybe even "Bro". It's sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding. But on the third day, Santiago is freakin' EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a fucking harpoon. It's a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words instead of giving in to base desires and imposing his gigantically terrible position on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, read to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding Marlin's carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you've finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to fucking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he's still unlucky, REALLY unlucky (DUH!) Ma calls the sharks "dream killers". Which isn't really all that fair, I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin... Jesus, don't even get me started on the marlin. It was just hanging out one day, minding it's own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it's family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who's the "Dream killer" now, fuckface! The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - He's super tired. The next morning, a group of fisherman gather around Santiago's boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit shingles! It's over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (Strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later there's a Red Lobster restaurant in nearly every city in America offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: The license plate on the car when he is in the phone booth says 338 EIN. If we add 3+3+8 you get 14. Using the letter to number conversion EIN comes out to 4+9+14 which equals 27. 27+14=41. The 4 represents the number of people in this trailer, and the 1 represents the number of Deadpool movies there have been. Crazy, right? But why stop there? If we add 4+1 we get 5. Then we subtract 2 because that's the number of how many swords Deadpool carries to get 3. Now we add 10 because (Including Logan) that's how many X-Men movies there have been. Now we subtract 1 because everyone hates X-Men Origins. We're left with 12. Now, there are four main storylines in the X-Men movies: Wolverine, modern X-Men, Deadpool, and the First Class trilogy. If we divide 12/4 we get 3 again. Bryan Singer is a great storyteller. You know what else has a great story? Half-Life. At long last, Half-Life 3 confirmed.

text: The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like... HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he's the unluckiest son of a bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it'd be so hard to NOT catch a fish... even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince Used to say, 'Parents Just Don't Understand.' So the boy visits Santiago's shack anyway, ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself. Manolin helps out, moving Santiago's fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he's going way out into the Gulf Stream, WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning! On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. HE's sure it's a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can't pull the monster in. Santiago's leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he's bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him "brother" or maybe even, "bro." It's sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding. But on the third day, Santiago is freakin' EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a fucking harpoon, it's a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words, instead giving in to base desires and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subjects through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin's carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you've finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to fucking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but he drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he's still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks, "dream killers", Which isn't really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin... Jesus, don't even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding its own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for its family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who's the real "dream killer" now, fuckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - he's super tired. The next morning, a group of fishermen gather around Santiago's boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It's over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee and when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there's a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like... HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he's the unluckiest son of a bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it'd be hard to NOT catch a fish... even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as the Fresh Prince used to say, Parents Just Don't Understand.' So the boy visits Santiago's shack anyway. Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself. Manolin helps out, moving Santiago's fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he's going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning! On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He's sure it's a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can't pull the monster in. Santiago's leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights and he holds on for dear life. Even though he's bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this might adversary. He starts calling him "brother" or maybe even "bro." It's sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding. But on the third day, Santiago is freakin' EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever he wants. So he stabs it. With a fucking harpoon. It's a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words instead giving in to base desires and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin's carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you've finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to fucking shreds while dry humping your dignity with their crazy weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he's still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks "dream killers". Which isn't really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin... Jesus, don't even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding its own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for its family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who's the "dream killer" now, fuckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said, he's super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago's boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit shingles! It's over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there's a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: In case anyone is wondering what was written at the end of the trailer..  The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like ‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it‚Äôd be hard NOT to catch a fish ‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago is so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as the Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄòParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand‚Äô. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway. Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food, and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio, who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the Gulf Stream, WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning! On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding. But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a fucking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words‚Äîinstead giving in to base desires‚Äîand imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to fucking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky, REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair, I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin ‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for its family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, fuckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said‚Äîhe‚Äôs super tired. The next morning, a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: A drug dealer, sells drugs, hoping to own his customers by getting them addicted.  From McD's to Apple Computer to Levi's jeans, "drug dealers" abound.  It is "the world", what they do. ... some, liken addictions to sexual activity, fleshly lusts.  Hence "fuck" can refer to  really good ice cream... A mother is somebody, or someone, who expresses unconditional love towards you, not expecting anything in return.  A mother, they say, is oft taken for granted, like the shade cast by a tree - missed, value realized, when the tree is no longer there, protecting you from the heat of the day... And so, a "motherfucker" would be somebody who looks upon a mother as a resource, the way some, such as drug dealers, see customers as dollar signs. But "motherfuckers" are worse, because they see mothers as "dollar signs", targets, prey, et cetra... This is not to say that it is ok to look upon some as a resource, but merely attempting to define that term, and the philosophy implied by that term.  Words can harm.  What is "bromance"?  Beware of words which do not appear in the bible, kjv... what are they tryimg to sell you?..  Does a physician see patients, or is he a businessman looking out for his own interest?... Music... is, or may be, spiritual food... ice cream... earthly, worldly, fleshly... that pleasure passes quickly, whereas music can really help you get through a "tough time".  But like liquor and drugs, music can also blind you as to how bad things really are, by creating a "high"... the woman is the weaker vessel... bribes, or gifts?  An attempt to purchase "love"? Or do you "see" (some things are invisible) Jesus, and a woman breaking a bottle of perfume over his head?... colateral... parallel.. duality... Some films, the language, fits, whereas in other films, you think the words spoken subtract from the story, add nothing.  But this writing is amazing.... Comic books, how addictive?  They tend to end on a cliffhanger, or the commencement of a new storyline, so you have to get the next issue... And then one day, they raise prices... The world, is not going away... but sometimes, you can see light shining in darkness...

text: Text at the end: üòÅ  The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it‚Äôd be hard to NOT catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄòParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand‚Äô. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway.  Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning!  On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f*cking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words - instead giving in to base desires - and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical.  Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f*cking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin.  Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f*ckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point.  Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - he‚Äôs super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man.  Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it‚Äôd be hard to NOT catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄòParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand‚Äô. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway.  Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning!  Deadpool 2 Firefly Deadpool 2s Teaser Text Included an Essay on The Old Man and The Sea On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.   But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f*cking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words ‚Äì instead giving in to base desires ‚Äì and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical.  Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f*cking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin.  Deadpool 2 Teaser with Ryan Reynolds Deadpool 2s Teaser Text Included an Essay on The Old Man and The Sea  Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f*ckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point.  Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said ‚Äì he‚Äôs super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man.  Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

He is given a certain amount of time to live and is exhausted by the lack of help that is avaliable, like how the fisherman is tired of the fruitless endveaor of catching fish. What Deadpool and the fisherman don't realize is that they are in over their head and are soon commanded by someone, or something else's will, and have no choice in what happens next. Deadpool becomes emotionally stranded like the fisher man after they are dragged far from where they know. Finally they've both had enough of this monster and finish him/it off. text: *Transcription of the text because I was bored. Idk if someone did that before*  "The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like... Huge. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he's the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it's be hard to NOT catch a fish... even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, 'Parents Just Don't Understand'. Do the boy visits Santiago's shack anyway. Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago's fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The nest day, Santiago tells Manolin that he's going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of cuba. Lady luck is returning! On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big-ass fish. He's sure it's a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can't pull the monster in. Santiago's leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even tough he's bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him "brother" or maybe even, "bro". It's sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding. but on the third day, Santiago is freakin' EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he sayd and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a fucking harpoon. It's a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words - instead giving in to base desires - and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject trough unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin's carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you've finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to fucking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. Be nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he's still unlucky, REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks, "dream killers". Which isn't rally all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin... Jesus, don't even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it's own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it's family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who's the "dream killer" now, fuckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes i ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - he's super tired. The nest morning, a group of fishermen gather around Santiago's boat. One measures the skeleton and, hoyl shit-shingles! It's over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. many years later, there's a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking."

He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f*cking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words ‚Äì instead giving in to base desires ‚Äì and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical.  Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f*cking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin.  Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f*ckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point.  Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said ‚Äì he‚Äôs super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man.  Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: Here‚Äôs the text for your reading pleasure. Note that it contains not-safe-for-work language.  ‚ÄúThe Old Man and the Sea‚Äù is the story of a fight between an elderly accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son of a bitch on planet earth. Honestly if you were in a boat for eighty four days, it‚Äôd be hard NOT to catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄúParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand.‚Äù  So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway, ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself. Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio, who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs¬†going out into the Gulf Stream, WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady lucky is returning!  On the eighty fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the¬†reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f‚Äîing harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words ‚Äî instead giving into base desires ‚Äî and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subect through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hit the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price.  But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f‚Äîing shreds while dry humping your dignity with their crazy weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness.  Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. Really unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers.‚Äù Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair, I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding its own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for its family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f‚Äîface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said ‚Äî he‚Äôs super tired.  The next morning, a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton, and, holy shit shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again.  Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: End Story:   "The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it‚Äôd be hard to NOT catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄòParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand‚Äô. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway.  Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning!  On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f*cking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words - instead giving in to base desires - and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical.  Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f*cking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin.  Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f*ckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point.  Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - he‚Äôs super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man.  Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking."

text: ‚ÄúThe Old Man and the Sea‚Äù is the story of a fight between an elderly accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son of a bitch on planet earth. Honestly if you were in a boat for eighty four days, it‚Äôd be hard NOT to catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄúParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand.‚Äù  So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway, ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself. Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio, who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going out into the Gulf Stream, WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady lucky is returning!  On the eighty fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f‚Äîing harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words ‚Äî instead giving into base desires ‚Äî and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subect through unblinking violence. Typical. Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hit the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price.  But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because as we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f‚Äîing shreds while dry humping your dignity with their crazy weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin. Only a bleach white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness.  Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. Really unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers.‚Äù Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair, I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding its own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for its family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f‚Äîface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point. Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said ‚Äî he‚Äôs super tired.  The next morning, a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton, and, holy shit shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man. Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again.  Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.

text: Someone already transcribed the scroll at the end: (3:28)  The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it‚Äôd be hard to NOT catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄòParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand‚Äô. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway.  Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning!  On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f*cking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words - instead giving in to base desires - and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical.  Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f*cking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin.  Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f*ckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point.  Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - he‚Äôs super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man.  Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking. (This story isn't mine BTW)

text: The Old Man and the Sea is the story of a fight between an elderly, accomplished fisherman, Santiago, and a really big fish. Like‚Ä¶ HUGE. The story opens with Santiago suffering eighty-four days without catching a fish because he‚Äôs the unluckiest son-of-a-bitch on planet earth. Honestly, if you were in a boat for eighty-four days, it‚Äôd be hard to NOT catch a fish‚Ä¶ even by accident. Santiago was so unlucky that his apprentice, Manolin, was forbidden by his Ma and Pa to fish with him. But as The Fresh Prince used to say, ‚ÄòParents Just Don‚Äôt Understand‚Äô. So the boy visits Santiago‚Äôs shack anyway.  Ignoring the inherent risks of unsupervised playtime with an elderly man who talks to himself, Manolin helps out, moving Santiago‚Äôs fishing gear, making food and talking about baseball. Especially Joe DiMaggio; who used to bump fuzzies with Marilyn Monroe. The next day, Santiago tells Manolin that he‚Äôs going way out into the Gulf Stream. WAY OUT north of Cuba. Lady luck is returning!  On the eighty-fifth day of his crappy luck, Santiago drops his lines, and by noon, gets a bite from what feels like a big ass fish. He‚Äôs sure it‚Äôs a winner. He fights and fights and fights but can‚Äôt pull the monster in. Santiago‚Äôs leaky old boat is pulled by the fish for two days and nights as he holds on for dear life. Even though he‚Äôs bloody and beat, Santiago begins to appreciate this mighty adversary. He starts calling him ‚Äúbrother‚Äù or maybe even, ‚Äúbro.‚Äù It‚Äôs sort of a love story if you really think about it. And like most romantic comedies, the reader pictures a delightful outfit changing montage, followed by the inevitable interspecies wedding.  But on the third day, Santiago is freakin‚Äô EXHAUSTED, and decides he just wants the fish to do what he says and not always swim wherever it wants. So he stabs it. With a f*cking harpoon. It‚Äôs a mess. Super gross. Blood everywhere. Because, like many men his age, Santiago has difficulty expressing his emotions and fears with words - instead giving in to base desires - and imposing his gigantically terrible positions on any given subject through unblinking violence. Typical.  Anyway, he straps the marlin to the side of his skiff and hits the road home, ready to act like a total show off to everyone and probably gouge people on the price. But guess what? Pretty soon sharks begin to attack the bleeding marlin‚Äôs carcass, because we all know, life is a tragic opera and just when you think you‚Äôve finally found something good and true, sharks come along and rip it all to f*cking shreds while dry-humping your dignity with their crazy-weird shark dicks. Sure, Santiago tries killing a few of them, but drops his harpoon because his hands are just as old as he is. By nighttime, the sharks have pretty much eaten the entire marlin.  Only a bleach-white skeleton remains, silently mocking him in the murky darkness. Santiago realizes he‚Äôs still unlucky. REALLY unlucky. (Duh!) He calls the sharks ‚Äúdream killers‚Äù. Which isn‚Äôt really all that fair. I mean, the sharks were just doing their job and the marlin‚Ä¶ Jesus, don‚Äôt even get me started on the marlin! It was just hanging out one day, minding it‚Äôs own business, maybe thinking about ways it could be a better provider for it‚Äôs family and WHAM! Harpoon in the brain. Who‚Äôs the ‚Äúdream killer‚Äù now, f*ckface? The hypocrisy is pretty much boundless at this point.  Eventually Santiago makes it ashore. Leaving the bones of the marlin and the boat, he hobbles to his shack. He makes it home and crashes, like I said - he‚Äôs super tired. The next morning a group of fishermen gather around Santiago‚Äôs boat. One measures the skeleton and, holy shit-shingles! It‚Äôs over 18 feet! The head of the fish is given to Pedrico (strange that this is the first mention of him) and the other fishermen ask Manolin to send their glad tidings to the old man.  Manolin brings Santiago newspapers and coffee when he wakes and they decide to fish together again. Many years later, there‚Äôs a Red Lobster Restaurant in nearly every city in America, offering a casual dining experience and convenient parking.
